elements.title: Calvin Duncan
elements.contents: ... that Calvin Duncan (pictured) was elected clerk of the same court that wrongfully convicted him of murder and sentenced him to life in prison?

elements.title: Billy Gallagher
elements.contents: ... that Billy Gallagher's Times Square cabaret was open from sundown to dawn, with a mix of "reputable people" and those "who had practical reasons for circulating after dark"?

elements.title: Rena Motomura

elements.title: Al-Qunayyah
elements.contents: ... that Al-Qunayyah, a village in Jordan, is thought to have been the site of a Roman-era sanctuary?

elements.title: Kent Kammerer
elements.contents: ... that to teach high school photography, Kent Kammerer took students on trips to the North Cascades and Olympic Peninsula in a home-built camper?

elements.contents: ... that Astor Piazzolla's Oblivion has been called "exquisitely melancholic"?

elements.title: Kamaipuʻupaʻa
elements.contents: ... that Kamaipuʻupaʻa, the mistress of King Kamehameha V, blamed the 1871 Lānaʻi earthquake on a foreigner riding a horse?
